It pertaineth to the pastoral office for a provident shepherd to exercise an ever watchful care over the state of the churches and the welfare of souls committed to his care, so as, having to give an account of the flock entrusted to him, he may without failing be able to return the gain on the talent com- mitted to him. This is why, of those things which in former time were or- dained by the ancient fathers, we recall to mind certain at these presents, add- ing to them a few [things] de novo, that we may not seem by dissembling (which be it far from us) to neglect the rule committed to us.
